<div id="review_4028769892" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4028769892" />
    <a title="Celeste" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32415957-celeste"><img alt="Celeste" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590400055p2/32415957.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4028769892?book_show_action=true">May 29, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Celeste" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Celeste" href="/user/show/32415957-celeste">Celeste</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780393355543" href="/book/show/35187179-the-conference-of-the-birds">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4028769892" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13919746264849838115">“How arrogant you are<br/>To think your wretched self so singular! <br/>The disappointments of the world will die<br/>In less time than the blinking of an eye,<br/>And as the earth must pass, pass by the earth —<br/>Don’t even glance at it, know what it’s worth”<br/><br/>This was the excerpt that caught my eye and first introduced me to Conference of the Birds. I might have seen it on Tumblr years ago. The imagery stuck with me — of a multitude of birds conferring amongst themselves. What would they say of man’s folly; what did t</span>
  <span id="freeText13919746264849838115" style="display:none">“How arrogant you are<br />To think your wretched self so singular! <br />The disappointments of the world will die<br />In less time than the blinking of an eye,<br />And as the earth must pass, pass by the earth —<br />Don’t even glance at it, know what it’s worth”<br /><br />This was the excerpt that caught my eye and first introduced me to Conference of the Birds. I might have seen it on Tumblr years ago. The imagery stuck with me — of a multitude of birds conferring amongst themselves. What would they say of man’s folly; what did the pigeons think when they looked into the windows of our high rise apartments and silently observed the affairs of man?<br /><br />In quite a wretched state I sought this book, hoping that its wisdom would deliver me from my emotional torments. The Conference of the Birds is a Persian poem written in 1177 AD, and I immensely enjoyed this English translation with an introduction at the beginning. It is written in a Q&amp;A format, where the birds of the world gather together to seek a king, and the wise bird, a hoopoe, acts as their spiritual guide and answers their questions by way of this poem. One of the main takeaways is that the Self is “an entity dependent on pride and reputation, there can be no progress until the pilgrim is indifferent to both, and the commonest way of making him indifferent is the experience of overwhelming love”. The birds make the Way through seven valleys and eventually reach the King; then they realise that the King was (in) themselves all along.<br /><br />This is the first book I read on Kindle, and I must say I am 100% a convert. I am also thankful for my Christian education growing up as this poem had references to the Old Testament, and enjoyed similarities between this and other mystical religions like Hinduism.<br /><br />Excerpts below:<br />*****<br /><br />The Self has swallowed you for its delight;<br />How long will you endure its mindless spite?<br />Cut off its head, seek out the moon, and fly<br />Beyond the utmost limits of the sky<br /><br />The ocean can be yours; why should you stop<br />Beguiled by dreams of evanescent dew?<br />The secrets of the sun are yours, but you<br />Content yourself with motes trapped in its beams.<br />Turn to what truly lives, reject what seems —<br />Which matters more, the body or the soul?<br />Be whole: desire and journey to the Whole.<br /><br />Your self-importance is ridiculous;<br />Why should a shadow merit so much fuss?<br /><br />I have no majesty since I have died;<br />Your greetings pierce my soul. That majesty<br />Was only ignorance and vanity;<br />True majesty belongs to God alone.<br /><br />A king with rivals in his dignity<br />Is no true king; the Sigmorgh rules alone<br />And entertains no rivals to his throne.<br />A king is not one of those common fools<br />Who snatched at a crown and think he rules.<br />The true king reigns in mild humility.<br /><br />How can love thrive<br />In hearts impoverished and half alive?<br />A man whose eyes love opens risks his soul—<br />His dancing breaks beyond the mind’s control.<br /><br />Of His perfect grace,<br />He makes a mirror in our hearts — look there<br />To see Him, search your hearts with anxious care.<br /><br />If you would glimpse the beauty we revere<br />Look in your heart — it’s image will appear.<br />Make of your heart a looking-glass and see<br />Reflected there the Friend’s nobility.<br /><br />Love thrives on inextinguishable pain,<br />Which tears the soul, then knits the threads again.<br />A mote of love exceeds all bounds; it gives<br />The vital essence to whatever lives.<br />But where love thrives, there is pain always found<br /><br />Love has no cure, and he could not obey.<br />(When did a lover listen to advice?)<br /><br />This fevered darkness and my wretched state<br />Were made when I was made, and are my fate;<br />Love consumes me through this endless night —<br />I yield to love, unequal to the fight.<br /><br />Love binds my feet and I cannot depart;<br />Love holds the hand pressed hard against my heart.<br /><br />I in love’s unhappy torments live and die;<br />To Love, both young and old are one — his dart<br />Strikes with unequalled strength in every heart.<br /><br />Though you are wise your wisdom cannot know<br />The wild frustrations through which lovers go.<br />If for one moment you could share my pain,<br />We could be old companions once again.<br /><br />The sea of righteousness drowns in its waves<br />The sins of those sincere repentance saves.<br /><br />We have no freedom to achieve our goal<br />Until from Self and fools we free the soul.<br />To be admitted past the veil you must<br />Be dead to all the crowd considers just.<br /><br />Love’s pain will murder him, then blandly ask<br />A surgeon’s fee for managing the task<br /><br />If from this whirlpool you can raise your head,<br />Tranquility will take the place of dread.<br /><br />The ocean of God’s Grace is infinite —<br />Our sins are like a tear dissolved in it,<br />One who accused sinners takes the part<br />Of the tyranny, and bears a tyrant’s heart.<br /><br />Do not despise yourself, for there is none<br />Who could with you sustain comparison;<br />Do not torment yourself — your soul is All,<br />Your body but a fleeting particle<br /><br />What man is truly single-minded? None!<br />If all of us could boast a spotless mind,<br />Why should the prophets mingle with mankind?<br />A hundred kindnesses will calm your cares.<br />Life is an obstinate young colt —<br />Until He’s broken in by your restraining will<br /><br />If you seem more substantial than a hair<br />You’ve made an idol of yourself — take care,<br />Whatever praise or blame may say of you,<br />You’re an isolated in all you do.<br /><br />You rush to savour life, and so life goes<br />While you ignore the balm for all its woes;<br />Until the Self is sacrificed your soul<br />Is lost in filth, divided from its goal.<br /><br />What seems tonight<br />So strange was certain from eternity;<br />What happens happens from necessity,<br /><br />“There’s nothing I can say,”<br />The man replied, “except that every day<br />I lived was wasted on what’s trivial<br />And now I shall be dust — and that is all.”<br /><br />I heard the sigh that tore your breast,<br />And knew I must accept you as you are,<br />Not seek for this or that particular —<br />Embrace the soul and disregard the pain,<br />Or weigh up what is loss and what is gain.<br /><br />Can one who craves the sun be satisfied<br />With petty ignorance? Is this his guide?<br /><br />The bird of aspiration spreads its wings<br />And quickly soars beyond terrestrial things —<br />Beyond the lower world’s complacent guess<br />Of what is temperance, what drunkenness.<br /><br />To turn from what we are, to yearn and die<br />Is not for us to choose or to deny.<br /><br />You cannot love, and this is why you seek<br />To find men vicious, or depraved, or weak —<br />If you could search for love and persevere<br />The sins of other men would disappear.<br /><br />Your sins are heavy, and while they are there,<br />Another’s guilt is none of your affair.<br /><br />In sighs rejoice, in longing persevere —<br />And if beneath the sky’s oppressive dome<br />Wounds scar you, you draw nearer to your home;<br />Don’t flinch from pain or search here for its cure.<br />Uncauterized your wounds must bleed; endure!<br /><br />Act with detachment now in everything.<br />Detachment is a flame, a livid flash,<br />That will reduce a hundred worlds to ash;<br />Its valley makes creation disappear,<br />And if the world has gone, then where is fear?<br /><br />And as she glimpsed his face she felt her heart,<br />Her intellect, her self-control depart —<br />Now reason fled and love usurped its reign;<br />Her sweet soul trembled in love’s bitter pain.<br />For days she meditated, struggled, strived<br />But bowed at last before the force of love<br />And gave herself to longing, to the fire<br />Of passionate, insatiable desire.<br /><br />If you cannot endure, how will you find<br />The promised peace that haunts your troubled mind?<br />You leapt like lightning once, yet now you stand<br />Like marshy water clogged with desert sand —<br />Renew your courage, put aside your fear<br />And in love’s fire let reason disappear.<br /><br />I too am lost; I leave no trace, no mark;<br />I am a shadow cast upon the dark,<br />A drop sunk in the sea, and it is vain<br />To search the sea for that one drop again<br /><br />Their souls rose free of all they’d been before;<br />The past and all its actions were no more.<br />Their life came from that close, insistent sun<br />And in its vivid rays they shone as one.<br /><br />“I am a mirror set before your eyes,<br />And all who come before my splendour see<br />Themselves, their own unique reality”</span>
  <a data-text-id="13919746264849838115" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
