<div id="review_782998582" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/782998582" />
    <a title="Troy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1851816-troy"><img alt="Troy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1231279778p2/1851816.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/782998582?book_show_action=true">Dec 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Troy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Troy" href="/user/show/1851816-troy">Troy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1851816-troy?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1851816-troy?shelf=read-in-2013">read-in-2013</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1851816-troy?shelf=gave-up-on">gave-up-on</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer782998582" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8525719733991139756">I&apos;m reading about Christian pastoral governance which is all about the renunciation of one&apos;s will, and one&apos;s obedience and subservience to your superiors, and ultimately, to God. And that&apos;s what this long poem is all about. Renounce your ego; renounce your will; abandon your desires; and be obedient to those that command you. Ultimately, be fully obedient to God.<br/><br/>Now, there are some aspects of this I can get behind, but this poem&apos;s obsequious and lachrymose obsession with obedience bores the shit</span>
  <span id="freeText8525719733991139756" style="display:none">I'm reading about Christian pastoral governance which is all about the renunciation of one's will, and one's obedience and subservience to your superiors, and ultimately, to God. And that's what this long poem is all about. Renounce your ego; renounce your will; abandon your desires; and be obedient to those that command you. Ultimately, be fully obedient to God.<br /><br />Now, there are some aspects of this I can get behind, but this poem's obsequious and lachrymose obsession with obedience bores the shit out of me. <br /><br />Worse, the poem, which is about an assembly of birds who join in a quest to find a holy king bird, is boring. A quest shouldn't be boring! But the quest is a tiny part of the poem. Most of the book is filled with whining birds who make hobbits look vainglorious. The birds ceaselessly complain and bitch, and each bird represents a base desire that is countered with lessons from their leader about what it means to be good and true. And maybe it's the translation, but where is the beauty in the prose? <br /><br />Now let me state that I dislike the ideology that surrounds me. But fuck these birds. I'm off to another poem and another philosophy. I'm not interested in obedience or God or total renunciation of one's will.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8525719733991139756" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


