<div id="review_1753440208" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1753440208" />
    <a title="James Violand" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6308377-james-violand"><img alt="James Violand" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1388703262p2/6308377.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1753440208?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James Violand" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James Violand" href="/user/show/6308377-james-violand">James Violand</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">those interested in Sufi poetry.</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6308377-james-violand?shelf=own">own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1753440208" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9144446792120350160">Attar was a wonderful poet, a confusing adherent of Islam and an extremely vain man who claimed Gabriel assisted him in writing this poem thereby equating himself with Mohammed. I cannot say for certain that he was a Sufi, nor that his &quot;way&quot; is unique. All of the great religions have mystics. What I can say from my experience in investigating these religions is that I believe this beautiful quest toward the Godhead is written with a very insulting and defensive position. It is as though a religi</span>
  <span id="freeText9144446792120350160" style="display:none">Attar was a wonderful poet, a confusing adherent of Islam and an extremely vain man who claimed Gabriel assisted him in writing this poem thereby equating himself with Mohammed. I cannot say for certain that he was a Sufi, nor that his "way" is unique. All of the great religions have mystics. What I can say from my experience in investigating these religions is that I believe this beautiful quest toward the Godhead is written with a very insulting and defensive position. It is as though a religion must denigrate all others to show its superiority. Some tales take a pathetic turn against those confessing their sins. And Attar brags about Omar burning down the Alexandria Library because it was filled with philosophy and contrary to the Koran. (This has been claimed as historical fact - but it isn't because it had ceased to exist long before Omar.) There is very little love shown one's fellow man, but he professes it toward God. The journey is an egoistic endeavor where one must ignore everything to pursue the journey. Instead of a guide to God in the guise of birds, I see ants climbing over one another in a struggle to be best.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9144446792120350160" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


