<div id="review_821685067" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/821685067" />
    <a title="Simin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10874745-simin"><img alt="Simin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1382184336p2/10874745.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/821685067?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Simin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Simin" href="/user/show/10874745-simin">Simin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer821685067" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7787054278671421123">This is the second book of Persian classical poetry book that I have read in its entirety. I used the online edition “Ganjour”, which contains the works of many Persian poets, both classical and contemporary. Ganjour provides access to the Persian dictionary by Dehkhoda, so looking up the definition of unfamiliar words was not a burden. I also listened to the audio edition of the book, narrated by Farid Hamed.<br/><br/>The Conference of the Birds is an introduction to Sufism.<br/>Since my knowledge of Sufism i</span>
  <span id="freeText7787054278671421123" style="display:none">This is the second book of Persian classical poetry book that I have read in its entirety. I used the online edition “Ganjour”, which contains the works of many Persian poets, both classical and contemporary. Ganjour provides access to the Persian dictionary by Dehkhoda, so looking up the definition of unfamiliar words was not a burden. I also listened to the audio edition of the book, narrated by Farid Hamed.<br /><br />The Conference of the Birds is an introduction to Sufism.<br />Since my knowledge of Sufism is extremely limited (ok… nonexistent!) I used 2 other sources: the lectures by the late Prof. Mahammad Jafar Mahjoub about Attar, and the English translation of the poem by Dick Davis. <br /><br />The book has a religious tone: Davis compares it to Dante’s Divine Comedy, in which both works describe religious belief in beautiful poetry. The prelude section is particularly heavy in that respect, and it was my least favorite part of the book.<br /><br />Although I believe I need much more reading about Sufism to comprehend the so many allegories in the book, I really enjoyed the beautiful poetry, especially when the birds speak!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7787054278671421123" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


